definition.value: A tetracyclic triterpenoid comprised of a lanostane skeleton which is 3beta-hydroxylated and has double bonds at the 9(11)- and 24-positions.
A tricyclic triterpenoid formed probably by cyclisation of (3S)-2,3-epoxy-2,3-dihydrosqualene to form an olean-13-yl cation with subsequent cleavage of the 8-14 and 9-10 bonds.

A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is picene which has been fully hydrogenated except for a double bond between the 4a and 5 positions and is substituted by methyl groups at the 4, 4, 6bbeta, 8abeta, 11, 11, 12balpha and 14bbeta positions, and by a hydroxy group at the 3beta position.

A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is perhydrochrysene which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 1, 1, 4bbeta, 6aalpha, 8beta and 10abeta positions, by a 4-methylpent-3-enyl group at the 8alpha position, and with a beta-oxygen bridge between the 2 and the 4a positions.

A triterpenoid that is (2S)-1,2,3,4,4a,5,8,8a-octahydronaphthalen-2-ol substituted by methyl groups at the 1, 1, 4a, and 6 positions and substituted at position 5 by a 2-[(4aR,7R,8S,8aR)-2,4a,7,8-tetramethyl-3,4,4a,5,6,7,8,8a-octahydronaphthalen-1-yl]ethyl group.

A triterpenoid and aldehyde that is 3-cyclohexylpropanal in which the cyclohexyl group is substituted by methyl groups at positions 2 and 3, by an (E,E)-4,8,12-trimethyltrideca-3,7,11-trien-1-yl group at position 2, and by a propan-2-ylidene group at position 6 (the 1S,2R,3R-enantiomer).

A triterpenoid that is (2S)-1,2,3,4,4a,5,8,8a-octahydronaphthalen-2-ol substituted by methyl groups at the 1, 1, 4a, and 6 positions and substituted at position 5 by a 2-[(4aR,8aR)-2,4a,7,7-tetramethyl-3,4,4a,5,6,7,8,8a-octahydronaphthalen-1-yl]ethyl group.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane which has a double bond between positions 13 and 18, and in which the hydrogen at the 3beta position is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A  tirucallane triterpenoid that is tirucalla-7,24-diene substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of 3-hydroxy-3-phenylpropionic acid.
A sulfur-containing amino acid whose alpha-carboxylic acid group is ionized (not protonated).
A branched-chain amino acid whose alpha-carboxylic acid group is ionized.
A modified amino acid whose alpha carboxylic acid group is ionized (not protonated).
An aromatic amino acid whose alpha-carboxylic acid group is ionized (non-protonated).
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of arsonoacetic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of ectoine.
A benzenesulfonate resulting from the deprotonation of both the carboxy group and the sulfo group of 4-carboxy-4'-sulfoazobenzene; the major species at pH 7.3.
An iodothyronine whose alpha carboxylic acid group of the tyrosine is ionized (not protonated).
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide obtained by formal condensation of the anilino group of P-(4-aminobenzyl)-N-(4-nitrophenyl)phosphonamidic acid with one of the carboxy groups of glutaric acid.
A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of (3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
A member of the class of phenylacetic acids in which the phenyl group is substituted by bromo, hydroxy, and nitro groups at position 3, 4, and 5 respectively.
An azide carrying a (3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of 6-[(3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetamido]caproic acid.
An N-acylamino acid that consists of 6-aminohexanoic acid bearing an N-(3-bromo-4-hydroxy-5-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
A tertiary amino compound that consists of glycine bearing two N-phosphonomethyl substituents.
A tertiary amino compound that consists of iminodiacetic acid bearing an N-phosphonomethyl substituent.
A triazolopyrimidine that consists of 3,6-dihydro-7H-[1,2,3]triazolo[4,5-d]pyrimidine bearing amino and oxo substituents at positions 5 and 7 respectively.
An azatricycloalkane that is tricyclo[6.2.1.1(3,6)]dodecane in which the four bridgehead CH groups are replaced by nitrogen atoms. It is a small-molecule BAX agonist.

A branched heptasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of three D-mannosyl residues and four N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.
An organic heterotricyclic compound containing one or more nitrogen atoms as part of the ring system.
A substance capable of undergoing rapid and highly exothermic decomposition.
A dithioloquinoxaline that is [1,3]dithiolo[4,5-b]quinoxaline in which both the hydrogens at position 2 are substituted by amino groups.

A branched octasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of one galactosyl residue, three D-mannosyl residues and four N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.
A polycyclic cage that is the S,S-dioxide of 9-thia-1,3,6,8-tetraazatricyclo[4.3.1.1(3,8)]undecane.

A branched nonasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of one galactosyl residue, three D-mannosyl residues and five N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.

A branched decasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of two galactosyl residues, three D-mannosyl residues and five N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.
A steroid saponin that consists of digoxigenin having a digitoxosyl residue attached at position 3.
A hydroxy steroid that consists of 5beta-cardanolide having a double bond at the 20(22)-position as well as hydroxy groups at the 3alpha,- 12beta- and 14beta-positions.
A steroid ester that is the 3,12-diacetyl derivative of digoxigenin.

A branched undecasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of three galactosyl residues, three D-mannosyl residues and five N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.

A branched dodecasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of one sialyl residue, three galactosyl residues, three D-mannosyl residues and five N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.

A branched tridecasaccharide glycosyl group consisisting of one fucosyl residue, one sialyl residue, three galactosyl residues, three D-mannosyl residues and five N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which is at the reducing end and commonly bonded to an amino acid residue.
A disaccharide glycosyl group consisting of a D-galactosyl group linked 1->4 to a D-xylosyl group.
A linear trisaccharide glycosyl group consisting of two galactosyl residues linked to a xylosyl residue at the reducing end.
A steroid ester that is the 3-acetyl derivative of gitoxigenin.
A linear tetrasaccharide glycosyl group consisting of one galacturonic acid resiue and two galactosyl residues linked to a xylosyl residue at the reducing end.

A linear pentasaccharide glycosyl group consisting of one N-acetylgalactosamine residue, one galacturonic acid residue, one fucosyl residue and two galactosyl residues linked to a xylosyl residue at the reducing end.
